President Joe Biden has announced his intention to nominate Paul K. Martin as Inspector General for the United States Agency for International Development (USAID). Martin currently serves as Inspector General for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) and has been Vice Chair of the Pandemic Response Accountability Committee since March 2020. He has previously held positions within the Department of Justice's Office of the Inspector General and the U.S. Sentencing Commission. Martin began his career as a reporter and holds a B.A. in Journalism and a Juris Doctor.

In addition, Biden intends to nominate Cardell K. Richardson, Sr. as Inspector General for the Department of State. Richardson currently serves as Inspector General for the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (NGA) and has a background in the U.S. Air Force, where he served for 26 years. He has been recognized with the Presidential Rank Award twice and holds degrees in architecture, public administration, and science.

Both nominees have extensive experience in oversight and leadership roles and will play key roles in the Biden administration.